{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530644"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:09:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:09:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14558"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14558"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.06,0.09,0.07,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7251"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56917"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7251","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7251"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14558"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42371"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"26"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1880"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"10964"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17626"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56917"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 52-year-old woman is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit with complications of severe pulmonary hypertension. She also has a history of systemic sclerosis diagnosed five years ago. Her regular medications include ambrisentan and furosemide. On examination, she appears unwell and dyspnoeic at rest.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following complications is most likely to be observed on further examination and investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Systemic hypertension","Bilateral upper limb weakness","Anaemia","A petechial rash","Hepatomegaly and ascites"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the patient is presenting with complications of severe pulmonary hypertension in the context of systemic sclerosis. Among the options provided, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehepatomegaly and ascites\u003C/strong\u003E are the most likely complications to be observed on examination and investigation. These findings are consistent with right heart failure, which is a common complication of severe pulmonary hypertension.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary hypertension leads to increased right ventricular afterload, causing right ventricular hypertrophy and eventually right heart failure. As the right ventricle fails, there is an increase in central venous pressure, which leads to congestion of the liver (hepatomegaly) and fluid accumulation in the peritoneal cavity (ascites). Other signs of right heart failure include peripheral oedema and elevated jugular venous pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnaemia\u003C/strong\u003E is not a direct complication of pulmonary hypertension and is less likely to be observed than hepatomegaly and ascites in this context. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epetechial rash\u003C/strong\u003E is also not typically associated with pulmonary hypertension. While systemic sclerosis can cause skin changes, petechiae are not a characteristic feature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely in this scenario. In fact, patients with severe pulmonary hypertension often have normal or low systemic blood pressure due to reduced left ventricular output. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBilateral upper limb weakness\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical complication of pulmonary hypertension. While systemic sclerosis can affect the musculoskeletal system, acute bilateral upper limb weakness would be an unusual presentation in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, hepatomegaly and ascites are the most likely complications to be observed in this patient with severe pulmonary hypertension, reflecting the development of right heart failure. Management would focus on optimizing treatment for pulmonary hypertension and addressing the right heart failure with diuretics and supportive care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Right heart failure secondary to severe pulmonary hypertension often leads to hepatomegaly and ascites due to increased central venous pressure.","Complications of severe pulmonary hypertension include right ventricular failure, hepatic congestion, and peripheral oedema."],"references":["Oldroyd SH, Manek G, Bhardwaj A. Pulmonary Hypertension. [Updated 2024 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482463/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42371"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14558"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/42371"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-22T15:01:43+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-22T15:02:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7251"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56917"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"